DENGUE-LIKE FEVER - SAMOA AND FIJI (02)
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
Date: Wed, 01 Oct 1997 18:21:23 -0700
From: Steve Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
[see
Dengue-like fever - Samoa and Fiji 970930192530
[Steve Berger, Tel Aviv Medical Center, has been kind enough to send us the
following summary via GIDEON, which is commercially available from Steve.
-- Mod CHC]
The following background information on dengue in these countries was
abstracted from GIDEON software:
Samoa:
An epidemic was reported in 1972. 248 cases (non fatal) were reported in 1979.
43 cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever were reported during 1980 to 1984; 450
during 1985 to 1989; 2 during 1990 to 1993.
Fiji:
Sporadic cases were reported during 1945 to 1970. Epidemics occurred in 1971
(3,400 cases - none hemorrhagic, with evidence of an additional 20,000
subclinical infections); and 1975 (16,203 cases, with several hemorrhagic;
50,000 subclinical infections estimated).
Four nonfatal cases of DHF werereported in 1979. 230 cases of DHF were
reported
during 1980 to 1984; 501 during 1985 to 1989; 619 during 1990 to 1993.
127 cases of dengue were reported in 1980; 18 in 1981; 581 in 1982; 237 in
1983; 190 in 1984; 229 in 1986; 1 in 1987; 22 in 1988; 2,225 in 1989. 1,473
cases (30 fatal) were reported in 1990, of whom 60% were Fijians and 37%
Indians. 65 cases (8 fatal) were reported in 1991; 349 in 1992. 27
suspected cases were reported during the period January to May 1995.
